conditionals:
## Overview
Conditionals let a Java program choose between different branches. The most common tools are `if`, `else if`, `else`, and the ternary operator.

## Key Points
- Java conditions must evaluate to `boolean`.
- `if` chains are best for multiple mutually exclusive cases.
- The ternary operator is useful when you want to choose one value.

## Example
```java
int points = 72;
String result;

if (points >= 50) {
  result = "pass";
} else {
  result = "fail";
}
```
The branch taken depends on whether the condition evaluates to `true` or `false`.

## Common Mistakes
- Writing deeply nested `if` blocks without simplifying the logic.
- Using the ternary operator for long, hard-to-read expressions.
- Forgetting braces in multi-line branches.

## Best Practices
- Keep conditions readable and focused.
- Use braces consistently, even for short branches.
- Extract complex boolean logic into helper methods when needed.

classes-objects:
## Overview
A class describes the structure and behavior of objects. Creating an object with `new` produces an instance with its own state.

## Key Points
- Fields store state and methods define behavior.
- Objects are reference types, so variables store references to them.
- `toString()` is useful for readable logging and debugging.

## Example
```java
class Person {
  String name;

  Person(String name) {
    this.name = name;
  }

  @Override
  public String toString() {
    return "Person[name=" + name + "]";
  }
}
```
The class defines one field, a constructor, and a readable string representation.

## Common Mistakes
- Confusing a class definition with an object instance.
- Forgetting to initialize important fields.
- Relying on the default `toString()` for meaningful output.

## Best Practices
- Model a clear responsibility per class.
- Keep object state valid from the start.
- Override `toString()` when readable diagnostics help.

constructors-this-super:
## Overview
Constructors prepare a new object for use. `this` refers to the current object, while `super` gives access to the parent class constructor or members.

## Key Points
- A constructor has no return type and shares the class name.
- `this(...)` calls another constructor in the same class.
- `super(...)` calls a constructor in the parent class.

## Example
```java
class Person {
  Person(String name) {}
}

class Student extends Person {
  Student(String name) {
    super(name);
  }
}
```
The subclass constructor delegates initialization to its parent with `super(name)`.

## Common Mistakes
- Trying to call both `this(...)` and `super(...)` in the same constructor.
- Forgetting that constructor chaining must be the first statement.
- Shadowing fields without using `this` clearly.

## Best Practices
- Centralize shared initialization through constructor chaining.
- Use `this.field = parameter` when names intentionally match.
- Keep constructors focused on establishing valid state.

encapsulation-access-modifiers:
## Overview
Encapsulation protects internal state and exposes only the operations an object should support. Access modifiers control which code can see fields, methods, and classes.

## Key Points
- `private` hides implementation details inside the class.
- `public` exposes an API to all callers.
- `protected` and package-private provide more limited visibility.

## Example
```java
class BankAccount {
  private int balance;

  public void deposit(int amount) {
    if (amount > 0) {
      balance += amount;
    }
  }
}
```
The class keeps `balance` private and allows controlled changes through `deposit`.

## Common Mistakes
- Exposing mutable fields directly.
- Adding trivial getters and setters without protecting invariants.
- Using `protected` when package-private or `private` would be safer.

## Best Practices
- Hide representation details behind methods.
- Validate state changes at the class boundary.
- Expose the smallest API that clients actually need.

equals-hashcode-contract:
## Overview
`equals()` defines logical equality between objects, and `hashCode()` must stay consistent with it. Hash-based collections such as `HashSet` and `HashMap` depend on this contract.

## Key Points
- Equal objects must produce the same hash code.
- `equals()` should be reflexive, symmetric, transitive, and consistent.
- Immutable equality fields make correct implementations easier.

## Example
```java
import java.util.Objects;

class Point {
  private final int x;
  private final int y;

  Point(int x, int y) {
    this.x = x;
    this.y = y;
  }

  @Override
  public boolean equals(Object obj) {
    if (this == obj) return true;
    if (!(obj instanceof Point other)) return false;
    return x == other.x && y == other.y;
  }

  @Override
  public int hashCode() {
    return Objects.hash(x, y);
  }
}
```
The class compares objects by value and builds a matching hash code from the same fields.

## Common Mistakes
- Overriding `equals()` without overriding `hashCode()`.
- Comparing the wrong fields or mutable fields.
- Using `==` when logical equality is required.

## Best Practices
- Base equality on the same meaningful fields every time.
- Prefer immutable fields for equality logic.
- Consider records when a class is mainly value-based data.

inheritance-polymorphism:
## Overview
Inheritance lets one class build on another, and polymorphism lets the program choose overridden behavior at runtime through a base type reference. Together, they enable reusable abstractions.

## Key Points
- `extends` creates an inheritance relationship.
- Overriding changes inherited behavior in a subclass.
- A base-type reference can point to different subtype instances.

## Example
```java
class Animal {
  void speak() {
    System.out.println("sound");
  }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
  @Override
  void speak() {
    System.out.println("bark");
  }
}
```
Calling `speak()` on an `Animal` reference still uses the `Dog` implementation when the actual object is a `Dog`.

## Common Mistakes
- Using inheritance only for code reuse when there is no real is-a relationship.
- Forgetting `@Override`, which makes mistakes harder to spot.
- Expecting subtype-specific members through a base reference without casting.

## Best Practices
- Use inheritance for real abstraction hierarchies.
- Favor composition when inheritance would be artificial.
- Keep parent classes stable and focused on shared behavior.

interfaces-abstract-classes:
## Overview
Interfaces and abstract classes both support abstraction, but they solve different design problems. Interfaces define capabilities, while abstract classes can also provide shared state and partial implementation.

## Key Points
- A class can implement multiple interfaces.
- A class can extend only one class, abstract or concrete.
- Interfaces are ideal for contracts; abstract classes are useful when related types share code or fields.

## Example
```java
interface Drawable {
  void draw();
}

abstract class Shape implements Drawable {
  protected final String color;

  Shape(String color) {
    this.color = color;
  }
}
```
The interface defines required behavior, while the abstract class stores shared state.

## Common Mistakes
- Choosing an abstract class when only a contract is needed.
- Forcing unrelated types into the same inheritance tree.
- Forgetting that interfaces can also contain default methods.

## Best Practices
- Use interfaces for flexible, loosely coupled APIs.
- Use abstract classes when common implementation is valuable.
- Keep abstractions small and coherent.

exception-handling:
## Overview
Exceptions signal abnormal situations in Java. Checked exceptions must be handled or declared, while unchecked exceptions usually indicate programming errors or invalid state.

## Key Points
- `try` contains risky code, `catch` handles failures, and `finally` runs cleanup logic.
- `throws` passes responsibility to the caller.
- Catching a specific exception is usually better than catching `Exception` broadly.

## Example
```java
try {
  int result = 10 / 0;
  System.out.println(result);
} catch (ArithmeticException ex) {
  System.out.println(ex.getMessage());
} finally {
  System.out.println("done");
}
```
The `catch` block handles the arithmetic failure, and `finally` still runs afterward.

## Common Mistakes
- Swallowing exceptions without logging or recovery.
- Catching types that are too broad.
- Using exceptions for normal control flow.

## Best Practices
- Handle exceptions where you can add context or recover.
- Use try-with-resources for closeable resources.
- Write messages and logs that help locate the real cause quickly.

generics:
## Overview
Generics let Java code express type parameters such as `List<String>` or `Box<T>`. They improve type safety by moving many errors from runtime to compile time.

## Key Points
- Type parameters make reusable APIs safer.
- Wildcards such as `? extends T` and `? super T` support flexible method signatures.
- Java generics use type erasure at runtime.

## Example
```java
class Box<T> {
  private T value;

  void set(T value) {
    this.value = value;
  }

  T get() {
    return value;
  }
}
```
`Box<T>` can store different types while preserving compile-time checks for each concrete use.

## Common Mistakes
- Using raw types like `List` instead of `List<String>`.
- Assuming `List<Object>` can replace `List<String>`.
- Ignoring wildcard bounds in API design.

## Best Practices
- Parameterize public collection types and reusable classes.
- Use upper and lower bounds when method flexibility is required.
- Prefer compile-time type safety over manual casts.
